#
# WHAT IS gosuri/uiprogress AND WHY IS IT THE 56TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# gosuri/uiprogress (https://github.com/gosuri/uiprogress, 2000+
# stars) is **Greg Osuri's "Go library for rendering progress bars
# in terminal applications"** — one of the FOUNDATIONAL Go
# terminal progress-bar libraries from the 2015 era, predating
# the modern Charm/Bubble Tea ecosystem.  Greg Osuri's `gosuri/`
# family (`uiprogress`, `uilive`, `uitable`, `cli-app`) was the
# canonical Go terminal UI toolkit before vbauerster/mpb,
# schollz/progressbar, and the Charm libraries took over the
# space.
#
# uiprogress's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. PROGRESS + uilive INTEGRATION — uiprogress depends on
#      gosuri/uilive (Greg's "real-time output for terminal" lib)
#      to handle:
#         - Cursor positioning across multiple bars
#         - Line erasure + redraw on terminal updates
#         - Refresh-rate control (auto + manual flush)
#      The PAIRED ABSTRACTION: uilive does live terminal-line
#      management, uiprogress builds bar widgets on top.
#
#          import "github.com/gosuri/uiprogress"
#
#          uiprogress.Start()             // start global progress writer
#
#          bar1 := uiprogress.AddBar(100) // bar with capacity 100
#              .AppendCompleted()
#              .PrependElapsed()
#
#          bar2 := uiprogress.AddBar(50)  // multi-bar
#              .AppendCompleted()
#
#          for bar1.Incr() {              // chained increment
#              time.Sleep(time.Millisecond * 20)
#          }
#
#          uiprogress.Stop()              // restore terminal
#
#      Compare:
#         * vbauerster/mpb (R559): similar multi-bar but with
#                                    priority queues + bar deps
#         * schollz/progressbar (R571): single-bar focused
#         * uiprogress + uilive: PAIR of libraries from gosuri
#                                 family (one for terminal
#                                 management, one for bars)
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with paired uilive
#      terminal-management dependency.
#
#   2. DECORATOR FUNCTIONS FOR PREFIX/SUFFIX — uiprogress uses
#      DECORATOR FUNCTIONS attached to each bar:
#         * AppendCompleted() — adds "X%" at end
#         * PrependElapsed()  — adds "elapsed: 5s" at start
#         * AppendFunc(func)  — custom append function
#         * PrependFunc(func) — custom prepend function
#
#      Custom decorators receive the Bar value + can render
#      arbitrary text:
#
#          bar.AppendFunc(func(b *uiprogress.Bar) string {
#              return fmt.Sprintf("(%d/%d)", b.Current(), b.Total)
#          })
#
#          bar.PrependFunc(func(b *uiprogress.Bar) string {
#              return strutil.Resize(label, 20)
#          })
#
#      Compare:
#         * mpb: similar decorator approach with mpb.Decor*
#                 functions
#         * schollz/progressbar: pre-defined format strings
#         * uiprogress: FUNCTION-BASED DECORATORS for prefix/
#                        suffix
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with function-
#      based decorator API (mpb borrowed this idea).
#
#   3. CHAINED .Incr() FOR ITERATION CONTROL — uiprogress's
#      `Incr()` method returns a BOOLEAN: true when incremented
#      successfully (within total), false when at capacity.
#      This makes it trivial to use as a loop condition:
#
#          for bar.Incr() {
#              do_work()
#          }
#
#      Equivalent to:
#
#          for i := 0; i < total; i++ {
#              bar.Incr()
#              do_work()
#          }
#
#      But more idiomatic Go.  Compare:
#         * mpb: explicit bar.Increment() calls
#         * schollz/progressbar: bar.Add(n) calls
#         * uiprogress: bar.Incr() returns bool for loop control
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with bool-returning
#      Incr() for natural for-loop integration.
#
#   4. WIDTH-AUTO-FIT TO TERMINAL — uiprogress's RefreshInterval
#      + terminal-width detection (via mattn/go-isatty +
#      mattn/go-runewidth) automatically sizes bars to the
#      terminal's column count.  Resizing the terminal
#      mid-execution updates bar widths on next refresh.
#      Compare:
#         * mpb: similar auto-fit
#         * schollz/progressbar: configurable width via
#                                  OptionSetWidth
#         * uiprogress: AUTO-FIT to terminal columns by default
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with default
#      terminal-column auto-fit.
#
#   5. GOSURI-ECOSYSTEM 2015-ERA PROVENANCE — gosuri/uiprogress
#      is part of Greg Osuri's pioneering Go terminal-UI
#      family from 2015 (predating Charm's bubbletea/lipgloss
#      by 5+ years).  The gosuri ecosystem:
#         * gosuri/uiprogress — progress bars (THIS)
#         * gosuri/uilive — live terminal-line management
#         * gosuri/uitable — terminal tables
#         * gosuri/cli-app — minimal CLI framework
#      Major historical users:
#         * mysql_random_data_load (THIS — Percona-Lab)
#         * video-downloader tools
#         * topfreegames/podium benchmark scripts
#         * jkomoros/sudoku puzzle generator
#         * orivej/git-compose
#         * Many 2015-2018 era Go CLI tools
#      Compare:
#         * mpb: emerged 2018+, modern concurrent design
#         * schollz/progressbar: Zack Scholl's family from 2017+
#         * uiprogress: gosuri family from 2015 — THE
#                        FOUNDATIONAL Go terminal-UI generation
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with 2015-era
#      foundational provenance + gosuri family ecosystem.
#
# uiprogress's relationship to other documented Go Axis 3
# libraries:
#
#   * Like vbauerster/mpb (R559) — both support multi-bar
#                                   composition
#   * Unlike mpb — uiprogress uses paired uilive + decorator-
#                   functions; mpb has integrated terminal +
#                   chained decorators
#   * Like schollz/progressbar (R571) — both have idiomatic
#                                        Go interfaces
#   * Unlike schollz/progressbar — uiprogress is multi-bar-
#                                   focused; schollz is single-
#                                   bar-focused
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: indicatif (R522) — closest design parallel
#                  with multi-bar coordination + decorators
#         * TS-Node: cli-progress (R560) — similar multi-bar
#                     concept
#         * Python: tqdm — most-iconic terminal progress library
#     uiprogress is the FIRST documented Go progress library
#     with paired uilive + decorator-functions + 2015-era
#     gosuri-ecosystem provenance.
#
